gh likeness and minimal difference, rather than individuality and identity. Reading for singularity shows us the ways femininity is fundamentally entangled with racial difference in the nineteenth century and well into the contemporary, as well as how rigid categories can be unsettled and upended. Grappling with the ongoing violence embedded in the Western liberal imaginary, Feminine Singularity invites readers to commune with the subversive potentials in nineteenth-century literature for thinking subjectivity today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFemininity in literature. 0aFrench literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSubjectivity in literature. 0aWomen in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  adifference.  afemininity.  afeminism.  alikeness.  anineteenth century.  asingularity.  asubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363231840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632318/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles